## CHARACTERS

### MILO VOSS

**What he is:** A lich. Mid-level arcane systems analyst at Aeon Holdings. Formerly one of the most gifted mages to come out of the Academy in a generation.

**What he was:** Brilliant, intense, probably difficult to be around. The kind of student who corrected professors and was right every time. He burned through his twenties trying to *do something* with his talent — research, innovation, pushing boundaries. He hit the wall that all geniuses in bureaucratic systems hit: the system doesn't want brilliance. It wants compliance. Rather than rage against it, he optimized. If the system wants to drain me, he reasoned, I'll do it on my terms. He designed his own lichdom ritual — elegant, efficient, painless. He walked into undeath the way an engineer solves a problem. No drama. No existential crisis. Just... a decision.

**What he tells himself:** That it was rational. That mortality is an engineering problem and he solved it. That he's free now — free from hunger, fear, pain, need. He can spend eternity reading, tending his plants, existing without the tyranny of a body that demands and decays.

**What's actually true:** He was exhausted and afraid and lonely and he chose numbness because it was easier than continuing to feel all of that. He's not at peace. He's in storage.

**His magic:** Exquisite control. Milo's spellwork is watchmaker-precise. He can unravel an enchantment thread by thread, build arcane systems of extraordinary complexity, sense magical currents the way a sommelier tastes wine. He's wasting roughly 95% of his ability on corporate busywork and he knows it. He doesn't care. (He tells himself he doesn't care.)

**Voice:** Dry. Deadpan. Observational. He narrates his own existence with a kind of detached amusement that almost hides the emptiness underneath. Heavy user of understatement.

**Habits:** Still makes coffee every morning (doesn't drink it, likes the ritual). Feeds his zombie cat, Mr. Bones, with unnecessary precision. Maintains his carnivorous plants with genuine care — they're the one thing he's kept from his living days. Gets to work exactly on time. Leaves exactly on time. Exists in the gaps between obligation with a stillness that would be meditative if it weren't so hollow.

**Sample voice:**
- *"I died on a Tuesday. Not dramatically — there was paperwork. HR was very supportive."*
- *"The thing about not needing to sleep is that the nights are exactly as long as they sound."*
- *[on Zara] "She ate lunch like it was a competitive sport and she was going for the gold in enthusiasm."*
- *[on being asked if he's happy] "I'm optimal. It's not the same thing, but it's more maintainable."*
- *"I used to be one of the most talented mages of my generation. Now I audit ward matrices for a company that sells enchanted office furniture. The system works."*
- *[on his zombie cat] "Mr. Bones has been dead for six years and still demands to be fed at exactly 6 AM. Death changes less than you'd think."*

