**Chapter 1 — Morning Routine**

Open on Milo's morning. First-person narration, bone-dry.

His apartment is clean, minimal, and precisely organized. He makes coffee — a full ritual, grinding beans, heating water to exact temperature — and sets the mug on the counter. Doesn't drink it. Likes the warmth against his hands, likes the smell (one of the few sensory pleasures that persists past the transition). Feeds Mr. Bones, who demands wet food with the imperious confidence of a creature unbothered by his own death. Tends his carnivorous plants — a Venus flytrap named Audrey (obvious reference, he's aware), a sundew, and a large pitcher plant that has, on occasion, eaten birds. He talks to them. Not in a cute way. In a "these are the only living things in my space and I maintain them with the same precision I maintain everything" way.

The commute establishes the world. The city is modern, familiar — but threaded with magic. Ward-signs on buildings like fire safety placards. Enchanted transit. A zombie street-sweeper working the early shift, and nobody looks twice. Milo passes living people and undead people, and the narration treats them identically, because to Milo there isn't much difference. He notes the living ones with a faint anthropological interest — the way they rush, the way they worry, the way they want things. *Exhausting.*

Aeon Holdings. Glass tower. He badges in, rides the elevator, sits at his desk. His work is auditing arcane ward systems — complex, demanding work that he does with about 10% of his attention. The rest just... idles. His cubicle neighbor is a lich who hasn't spoken unprompted in thirty years. Milo respects this.

We establish: this is a man who has solved the equation of living and the answer was zero.

*"People ask me if I miss being alive. That's like asking if I miss commuting — I remember that it took a lot of energy and involved a great deal of sitting in traffic, and I'm genuinely unclear on what I'm supposed to be nostalgic about."*

---

**Chapter 2 — The Machine**

Worldbuilding chapter, delivered through Milo's workday.

We see the layers of Aeon. Living employees on the upper floors, trending younger, brighter, more chaotic. Undead on the middle floors — quieter, more efficient, the backbone of operations. The sub-basements, where the really old infrastructure hums and the phylactery vault sits behind seventeen layers of warding that Milo helped design.

We meet Gerald in accounting, who nods at Milo in the elevator. They've had this non-verbal relationship for twenty years. It's the closest thing Milo has to a friendship.

We meet Harris, sweating through a meeting, performing enthusiasm with the desperate energy of a man who can feel himself becoming hollow and is trying to outrun it.

We see the "Transition Support" office — a pleasant room with brochures. "Your Next Chapter: A Guide to Post-Vital Employment." The woman running it is alive and deeply, unknowingly ironic.

Staff meeting. The department head (a lich, of course) discusses quarterly targets with the charisma of a spreadsheet reading itself aloud. Milo's narration drifts, providing us with his history in fragments — the Academy, his talent, the years of trying, the decision. He doesn't frame it as a tragedy. He frames it as engineering.

*"The pamphlet said, 'Lichdom: Because You've Given So Much Already.' Which was technically accurate. The 'so much' in question being your soul, and the 'already' being the last nine years of accounts receivable."*

We get a brief glimpse of the CEL — Edric Thane, crossing the lobby. The way every undead employee slightly orients toward him, like iron filings near a magnet. Milo feels it too. He doesn't think about it.

---

**Chapter 3 — The Disruption**

Zara's first day.

Milo doesn't meet her directly. He *notices* her, the way a seismograph notices a tremor. Something shifts in the ambient magical field of the building — a warmth, a ripple, like someone opened a window in a building that's been sealed for decades.

We see her through glimpses and secondhand reports. The break room after she's been there: someone's leftover salad has sprouted. A motivational poster ("Synergy Is Strength!") has, inexplicably, become slightly more sincere. Two undead employees in the hallway are arguing — actually arguing, with emotion — for the first time in years, about something trivial. The air smells different on her floor. Like rain.

Milo investigates the way he does everything — clinically. He checks the ward systems for anomalies. He scans the magical field. What he finds isn't a spell. It's not structured. It's just... *life,* radiating out from a single source like body heat, and his equipment barely knows how to measure it because it's not magic in any way the system is built to recognize.

He finds her in the break room, eating lunch with an enthusiasm that borders on performance art. She's telling a story to a table of coworkers (two living, one undead) and all of them are *leaning in.* The undead one is making an expression. Milo hasn't seen that particular lich make an expression in fifteen years.

He watches. He's not interested. He's *curious.* There's a difference. (There isn't.)

*"She ate a sandwich the way other people experience religion — with total commitment and an intensity that made everyone nearby question their own choices."*

